akes up not only the current state of literature and its criticism but also connections between contemporary philosophy and contemporary fiction. In doing so, the contributors aim to provoke further discussion of the present inflection of fiction—a present that can be seen as Janus-faced, looking both forward to the novel's radically changed, political, economic, and technological circumstances, and back to its history of achievements and problems.Editors R. M. Berry and Jeffrey R. Di Leo contend that examinations of fiction's present are most informative not when they defend philosophical distinctions or develop literary classifications, but when they grapple with elusive topics such as the meaning of a narrative present or the relation of fiction's medium to its representations of context. As the essays reveal, this process, when pursued diligently, breaks down traditional divisions of academic and intellectual labor, compelling the fiction writer to become more philosophical and the theorist to become more imaginative. The value of this book is not in the exhaustiveness of its treatment, but rather in the seriousness of the criticism it incites. The present materializes in quarrel, and it is toward such a beginning that the writings in Fiction's Present work.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aGeneral Interest : Fiction. 4aLiterature : Literary Theory. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy of Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh1 aBerry, R. M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerry, R. M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCaserio, Robert L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDelany, Samuel R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDi Leo, Jeffrey R., econtributor.4ctb